'''Ben Glenn''' (born October 6, 1973) is a [[Public speaker|professional speaker]], who is also known as “The Chalkguy”.  Ben Glenn was diagnosed with [[Dyslexia]] and other [[Learning disability|Learning Disabilities]] while in [[grade school]]. As an adult he also learned that he has [[ADHD]] and suddenly everything about his life made perfect sense.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} When he speaks at an event, he has a huge canvas on stage. As he is talking to the audience, he starts to draw images.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=The Advocate - Baton Rouge, La.|first=Chante Dionne|last=Warren|date=October 20, 2001|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/theadvocate/access/85399287.html?dids=85399287:85399287&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+20%2C+2001&author=CHANTE+DIONNE+WARREN&pub=Advocate&desc=Delivering+a+message+Minister+overcomes+disability%2C+inspires+others+with+art&pqatl=google|title=Delivering a message Minister overcomes disability, inspires others with art}}</ref> He ties his message in with the [[drawing]] that he is creating. Although he is dyslexic, Glenn has written the books, “Simply Special: Learning to Love your ADHD”, “Big Enough: Finding Faith to Move Mountains” and “Common Grounds: Conversations about the Things that Matter Most”.<ref>[http://keynotespeakers.com/speaker_detail.php?speakerid=3612 Keynote Speabook sucks kers]</ref> He often speaks about his struggle with dyslexia and ADHD,<ref>{{cite news|title=Artist Chalks Up a Powerful Lesson|publisher=Chicago Tribune|first=Pat |last=Harper|date=December 23, 1998|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/37462325.html?dids=37462325:37462325&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Dec+23%2C+1998&author=Pat+Harper.+Special+to+the+Tribune.&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=ARTIST+CHALKS+UP+A+POWERFUL+LESSON+A+FORMER+SPECIAL-ED+STUDENT+ENCOURAGES+PUPILS+TO+ACCEPT+THOSE+WHO+ARE+DIFFERENT.&pqatl=google|quote=Glenn, 25, an artist and motivational speaker, draws on his own experience as a dyslexic special-education student to explain how hurtful the taunts from peers can be.}}</ref> in addition to the barriers of age, [[Race (classification of humans)|race]], [[gender]] and [[culture]]s.<ref>[http://www.ycmhome.org/whoyoullhear.html#benglenn Youth Conference Ministries] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312120116/http://www.ycmhome.org/whoyoullhear.html#benglenn |date=March 12, 2010 }}</ref>

