{{Infobox person | name = Hajj Mulla Ali Kani | image = Mullaalikani.jpg | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = Kan | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | nationality = Iranian | other_names = | occupation = Scholar | father = Ghorbanali Amoli | years_active = | known_for = Nullify [[Reuter concession]] | notable_works = Tuneup Seminary Marvi }}
'''Mulla Ali Kani''' ({{lang-fa|ملا علی کنی}}, (1888–1805) was an Iranian Shia muslim [[scholars]], [[philosopher]] and from individuals [[Iranian Constitutional Revolution]].<ref>[http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/kani-haj-molla-ali Encyclopædia Iranica ḤĀJ MOLLĀ ʿALI KANI]</ref><ref>[http://www.oral-history.ir/?page=post&id=4136 3rd Iran and British Colonization Confab calls for papers]</ref> He was in charge of religious affairs of Iran, and had a great influence on people and even on [[Naser al-Din Shah Qajar]] and his court.<ref>[https://publishing.cdlib.org/ucpressebooks/view?docId=ft0f59n6r9&chunk.id=d0e12594&toc.depth=1&toc.id=d0e11323&brand=ucpress 8 Clericalist Monarchy and Shi‘i Institution Building - California Digital Library]</ref> After the singing of the [[Reuter concession]] in 1873 which in practice made Iran a colony of Britain, Mulla Ali Kani wrote a letter to the King, Nasir al-Din Shah, and opposed this contract. He wrote that what Reuter gains through this contract even is more than what Britain gained in India. He also wrote that when there is a flaw in governmental affairs, it is religious scholars' duty to refer to it whether the king favor this or not and whether tries to correct it or not" and strongly asked the king to cancel the contract and dismiss the prime minister, who was behind signing this contract. As a result of these objections and even foreign objections to the contract, at last, Nasir al-Din Shah canceled the contract and removed the minister from the office.<ref>Taymuri, 'Asr bi-khabari, p.123-126; Nazim al-Islam Kirmani, Tarikh biydari Iranian, p. 135.</ref> Kani died in [[Tehran]], 1888 and was buried in the shrine of [[Shah-Abdol-Azim shrine]] in Rey.<ref>Samuel G. W. Benjamin, Persia and the Persians, London, 1887.</ref>
