'''Robert van Voren''' (publishing pseudonym of ''Johannes Baks'',{{sfn|Mykoliuk|2013}} {{lang-nl|Johannes Bax}},{{sfn|Boersema|2001}} born 7 July 1959, [[Montreal, Quebec]], Canada{{sfn|Voren|2009b|p=271}}) is a [[Dutch people|Dutch]] [[human rights activist]]{{sfn|Moran|2010}} and [[political scientist]].<ref>{{harvnb|Donskis|2009|p=314}}; {{harvnb|Mykoliuk|2013}}</ref>

He is a professor of Soviet and post-Soviet studies in the [[Ilia State University]] in [[Tbilisi]] ([[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]) and in the [[Vytautas Magnus University]] in [[Kaunas]] ([[Lithuania]])<ref>{{harvnb|Voren|2013c}}; {{harvnb|Clark|2014}}</ref> as well as Chief Executive of the [[Global Initiative on Psychiatry]].<ref>{{harvnb|Leygraf|2010}}; {{harvnb|Targum|Chaban|Mykhnyak|2013}}</ref>

== Biography ==
He was born on 7 July 1959, [[Montreal]],{{sfn|Voren|2009b|p=271}} [[Quebec]], Canada<ref>{{harvnb|Skorokhod|2013}}; {{harvnb|Wynnyckyj|1996}}</ref> and graduated from [[Amsterdam University]] in 1986.{{sfn|VMU|2014}} In the 1980s, he worked at the Bukovsky Foundation based in Amsterdam<ref>{{harvnb|Glasgow Herald|1987}}; {{harvnb|James|1985}}</ref> and since 1989 was the director of its successor, the Second World Center.{{sfn|RCP|2014}} Since 1980, he had regularly visited the [[Soviet Union]] including [[Ukraine]] and collected information on repression of dissidents,{{sfn|Dobryanskaya|2010}} as well as smuggling [[Samizdat]] publications to the west. In 1986, he became Chief Executive of the Global Initiative on Psychiatry.{{sfn|Dobryanskaya|2010}} He is also a Honorary Fellow of the British [[Royal College of Psychiatrists]] and Honorary Member of the Ukrainian Psychiatric Association.{{sfn|Donskis|2009|p=314}}  In 2005, he was knighted by [[Queen Beatrix]] of the Netherlands for his work as a human rights activist.{{sfn|Donskis|2009|p=314}} He has a Lithuanian citizenship{{sfn|Lumans|2014}} since 11 February 2003{{sfn|Voren|2009b|p=271}} and lives in [[Vilnius]].{{sfn|Lavrinenko|2015}}

Robert van Voren has published over a dozen books.{{sfn|VMU|2014}} His works cover [[political abuse of psychiatry in the Soviet Union]]<ref>{{harvnb|Voren|Bloch|1989}}; {{harvnb|Keukens|Voren|2007}}; {{harvs|txt|author=Voren|year1=1983|year2=1987|year3=2009a|year4=2009b}}; {{harvs|txt|author=Voren|year1=2010a|year2=2010b|year3=2010c|year4=2013a|year5=2013b|year6=2013c}}; {{harvs|txt|author=Voren|year1=2014|year2=2015a|year3=2015b}}</ref> and [[China]]<ref>{{harvs|txt|author=Voren|year1=2002a|year2=2002b}}</ref> and reforms of mental health in [[Eastern Europe]],<ref>{{harvnb|Voren|Whiteford|2000}}; {{harvnb|Tomov|Voren|Keukens|2006}}</ref> the former Soviet Union,{{sfn|Voren|2006}} [[Ukraine]],<ref>{{harvnb|Dobryanskaya|2010}}; {{harvnb|Myagkova|2012}}; {{harvnb|Voren|1992}}</ref> [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].<ref>{{harvnb|Rogers|Keukens|Voren|2006}}; {{harvnb|Makhashvili|Voren|2013}}</ref> Robert van Voren's contribution to reform of forensic psychiatry in states of the former Soviet Union is widely recognized.{{sfn|Gordon|2006}}

In 2015, he commented the [[Ukrainian crisis]] and the [[Russian military intervention in the Syrian Civil War]].<ref>{{harvs|txt|author=Voren|year1=2015c|year2=2015d|year3=2015e}}</ref>

Van Voren referred to the country in which he grew up, the Netherlands, as 'a wobbling overfed Christmas turkey', and to its people as 'greedy, self-serving, egocentric and above all fundamentally dissatisfied', and as 'convinced they are entitled', in the wake of the [[Dutch Ukraine–European Union Association Agreement referendum, 2016|Dutch referendum]] on the [[Ukraine–European Union Association Agreement]], with the result of which he was disappointed.<ref>[http://euromaidanpress.com/2016/04/06/dutch-referendum-a-painful-mistake] Dutch referendum a painful mistake, euromaidanpress, 6 April 2016</ref>

